04085nam a22006255i 9780822371625DE-B159720200928045905.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200928t20182018ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017051306  a97808223716257 a10.1515/97808223716252doi  a(DE-B1597)552066  a(OCoLC)1048186281  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aHQ18.N458bT67 2018 4aHQ18.N458bT67 2018 7aHIS0250002bisacsh04a392.60972/532231 aTortorici, Zeb, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSins against Nature :bSex and Archives in Colonial New Spain /cZeb Tortorici. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b21 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tA NOTE ON TRANSLATION -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1 Viscerality in the Archives -- t2 Impulses of the Archive -- t3 Archiving the Signs of Sodomy -- t4 To Deaden the Memory -- t5 Archives of Negligence -- t6 Desiring the Divine -- tCONCLUSION -- tAPPENDIX -- tLIST OF ARCHIVES -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Sins against Nature Zeb Tortorici explores the prosecution of sex acts in colonial New Spain (present-day Mexico, Guatemala, the US Southwest, and the Philippines) to examine the multiple ways bodies and desires come to be textually recorded and archived. Drawing on the records from over three hundred criminal and Inquisition cases between 1530 and 1821, Tortorici shows how the secular and ecclesiastical courts deployed the term contra natura-against nature-to try those accused of sodomy, bestiality, masturbation, erotic religious visions, priestly solicitation of sex during confession, and other forms of "unnatural" sex. Archival traces of the visceral reactions of witnesses, the accused, colonial authorities, notaries, translators, and others in these records demonstrate the primacy of affect and its importance to the Spanish documentation and regulation of these sins against nature. In foregrounding the logic that dictated which crimes were recorded and how they are mediated through the colonial archive, Tortorici recasts Iberian Atlantic history through the prism of the unnatural while showing how archives destabilize the bodies, desires, and social categories on which the history of sexuality is based.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzNew SpainxHistoryvSources. 0aSex crimesxInvestigationzNew SpainvSources. 0aSex customszNew SpainvSources. 0aSexxSocial aspectszNew Spain. 0aTrials (Sex crimes)zNew SpainvSources. 4aAHA Committee on Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender History book awards. 4aJohn Boswell Prize winner. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822371625zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822371625423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822371625.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles